# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cell-culture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cell-culture/293t] The HEK 293 cell line has been widely used in research for decades due to its reliable and fast growth and propensity for transfection.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The cell line is used by the biotechnology industry to produce therapeutic proteins and viruses for gene therapy as well as safety testing for a vast array of chemicals.
[src:cell-culture/293t] HEK 293 cells were generated in 1973 by transfection of cultures of normal human embryonic kidney cells with sheared adenovirus 5 DNA in Alex van der Eb's laboratory in Leiden, the Netherlands.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The cells were obtained from a single, aborted or miscarried fetus, the precise origin of which is unclear.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The cells were cultured by van der Eb; the transfection with adenoviral DNA was performed by Frank Graham, a post-doc in van der Eb's lab.
[src:cell-culture/293t] They were published in 1977 after Graham left Leiden for McMaster University.
[src:cell-culture/293t] They are called HEK since they originated in human embryonic kidney cultures, while the number 293 came from Graham's habit of numbering his experiments; the original HEK 293 cell clone was from his 293rd experiment.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Graham performed the transfection a total of eight times, obtaining just one clone of cells that were cultured for several months.
[src:cell-culture/293t] After presumably adapting to tissue culture, cells from this clone developed into the relatively stable HEK 293 line.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Subsequent analysis has shown that the transformation was brought about by inserting ~4.5 kilobases from the left arm of the adenoviral genome, which became incorporated into human chromosome 19.
[src:cell-culture/293t] For many years it was assumed that HEK 293 cells were generated by transformation of either a fibroblastic, endothelial or epithelial cell, all of which are abundant in kidneys.
[src:cell-culture/293t] However, the original adenovirus transformation was inefficient, suggesting that the cell that finally produced the HEK 293 line may have been unusual in some fashion.
[src:cell-culture/293t] A comprehensive study of the genomes and transcriptomes of HEK 293 and five derivative cell lines compared the HEK 293 transcriptome with that of human kidney, adrenal, pituitary and central nervous tissue.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The HEK 293 pattern most closely resembled that of adrenal cells, which have many neuronal properties.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Given the location of the adrenal gland (*adrenal* means "next to the kidney"), a few adrenal cells could plausibly have appeared in an embryonic kidney derived culture, and could be preferentially transformed by adenovirus.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Adenoviruses transform neuronal lineage cells much more efficiently than typical human kidney epithelial cells.
[src:cell-culture/293t] An embryonic adrenal precursor cell therefore seems the most likely origin cell of the HEK 293 line.
[src:cell-culture/293t] As a consequence, HEK 293 cells should not be used as an *in vitro* model of typical kidney cells.
[src:cell-culture/293t] HEK 293 cells have a complex karyotype, exhibiting two or more copies of each chromosome and with a modal chromosome number of 64.
[src:cell-culture/293t] They are described as hypotriploid, containing less than three times the number of chromosomes of a haploid human gamete.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Chromosomal abnormalities include a total of three copies of the X chromosomes and four copies of chromosome 17 and chromosome 22.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The presence of multiple X chromosomes and the lack of any trace of Y chromosome derived sequence suggest that the source fetus was female.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The 293T cell line was created in Michele Calos's lab at Stanford by stable transfection of the HEK 293 cell line with a plasmid encoding a temperature-sensitive mutant of the SV40 large T antigen; it was originally referred to as 293/*tsA1609neo*.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The first reference to the cell line as "293T" may be its use to create the BOSC23 packaging cell line for producing retroviral particles.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Multiple variants of HEK 293 have been reported.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The transfection used to create 293T (involving plasmid pRSV-1609) conferred neomycin/G418 resistance and expression of the tsA1609 allele of SV40 large T antigen; this allele is fully active at 33 °C (its permissive temperature), has substantial function at 37 °C, and is inactive at 40 °C.
[src:cell-culture/293t] 293T is very efficiently transfected with DNA (like its parent HEK 293).
[src:cell-culture/293t] Due to the expression of SV40 large T antigen, transfected plasmid DNAs that carry the SV40 origin of replication can replicate in 293T and will transiently maintain a high copy number; this can greatly increase the amount of recombinant protein or retrovirus that can be produced from the cells.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The full genome sequences of three different isolates of 293T have been determined.
[src:cell-culture/293t] They are quite similar to each other but show detectable divergence from the parental HEK 293 cell line.
[src:cell-culture/293t] This mutant strain does not express of the equilibrative nucleoside transporter ENT1.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The gene was knocked out using CRISPR-CAS9 and the cell line retains ENT2 expression.
[src:cell-culture/293t] HEK 293 cells are straightforward to grow in culture and to transfect.
[src:cell-culture/293t] They have been used as hosts for gene expression.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Typically, these experiments involve transfecting in a gene (or combination of genes) of interest, and then analyzing the expressed protein.
[src:cell-culture/293t] The widespread use of this cell line is due to its transfectability by the various techniques, including calcium phosphate method, achieving efficiencies approaching 100%.
[src:cell-culture/293t] HEK 293 cells were adapted to grow in suspension culture, as opposed to proliferation on plastic plates, in 1985.
[src:cell-culture/293t] This enabled the growth of large amounts of recombinant adenovirus vectors.
[src:cell-culture/293t] A more specific use of HEK 293 cells is in the propagation of adenoviral vectors.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Viruses offer an efficient means of delivering genes into cells, which they evolved to do, and are thus of great use as experimental tools.
[src:cell-culture/293t] However, as pathogens, they also present a risk to the experimenter.
[src:cell-culture/293t] This danger can be avoided by the use of viruses which lack key genes, and which are thus unable to replicate after entering a cell.
[src:cell-culture/293t] In order to propagate such viral vectors, a cell line that expresses the missing genes is required.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Since HEK 293 cells express a number of adenoviral genes, they can be used to propagate adenoviral vectors in which these genes (typically, E1 and E3) are deleted, such as AdEasy.
[src:cell-culture/293t] However, homologous recombination between the inserted cellular Ad5 sequence and the vector sequence, although rare, can restore the replication capacity to the vector.
[src:cell-culture/293t] An important variant of this cell line is the 293T cell line.
[src:cell-culture/293t] It contains the SV40 large T-antigen that allows for episomal replication of transfected plasmids containing the SV40 origin of replication.
[src:cell-culture/293t] This allows for amplification of transfected plasmids and extended temporal expression of desired gene products.
[src:cell-culture/293t] HEK 293, and especially HEK 293T, cells are commonly used for the production of various retroviral vectors.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Various retroviral packaging cell lines are also based on these cells.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Depending on various conditions, the gene expression of HEK 293 cells may vary.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Alvin Wong, a Catholic bioethicist, argues that despite the uncertainty over the origin of the embryonic cells used to obtain the cell line, one can infer that it came from a voluntary abortion.
[src:cell-culture/293t] To some, this may present an ethical dilemma for using HEK 293 and derivative products, such as vaccines and many medications.
[src:cell-culture/293t] During the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-vaccination activists noted that HEK 293 cells are used in the manufacturing of the Oxford–AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine (AKA AZD1222).
[src:cell-culture/293t] The cells are filtered out of the final products.
[src:cell-culture/293t] Regeneron Pharmaceuticals, the maker of REGN-COV2, a therapeutic antibody cocktail used to alleviate symptoms of patients with COVID-19, did not use HEK 293T cells to produce the antibody cocktail but did use those cells to assess the potency of the drug.
[src:cell-culture/293t] In response to ethical concerns of vaccine production, several strategies for clinicians to discuss with their patients have been suggested.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Hydrogel from wood-based nanofibrillated cellulose (NFC) is used as a matrix for 3D cell culture, providing a three-dimensional environment that more closely resembles the conditions found in living tissue.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] As plant based material, it does not contain any human- or animal-derived components.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Nanocellulose is instead derived from wood pulp that has been processed to create extremely small, nanoscale fibers.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] These fibers can be used to create a hydrogel, which is a type of material that is made up of a network of cross-linked polymer chains and is able to hold large amounts of water.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] As the natural extracellular matrix (ECM) is important in the survival, proliferation, differentiation and migration of the cells, hydrogels mimicking natural ECM structure are considered as potential approaches towards in vivo –like cell culturing.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] NFC fiber network structure and dimensions in hydrogel resemble human ECM.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Stiffness can be tuned to optimize the conditions for each cell type.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Shear-thinning property of the material makes the gel ready to use without cross-linking or gelification step.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] The nanocellulose hydrogel can be completely degraded by cellulase enzyme treatment while retaining the 3D cell structures.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] NFC hydrogel in 3D cell culture offers a platform for various biomedical applications.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Different cell lines and cell types have been cultured in NFC, including e.g. differentiation of human hepatic cells to functional organotypic cultures, and proliferation of human pluripotent stem cells.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Organotypic liver cell cultures can be used in drug discovery for testing liver toxicity and metabolism of the novel drug candidates.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] The possibility to use the hydrogel with robotic dispensers enables its use in high throughput screening (HTS) formats.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture-in-wood-based-nanocellulose-hydrogel] Additionally, 3D cell culture using wood-based nanocellulose hydrogel can be used for tissue engineering.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] A **3D cell culture** is an artificially created environment in which biological cells are permitted to grow or interact with their surroundings in all three dimensions.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Unlike 2D environments (e.g. a Petri dish), a 3D cell culture allows cells in vitro to grow in all directions, similar to how they would in vivo.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] These three-dimensional cultures are usually grown in bioreactors, small capsules in which the cells can grow into spheroids, or 3D cell colonies.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Approximately 300 spheroids are usually cultured per bioreactor.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] 3D cell cultures have been used in research for several decades.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] One of the first recorded approaches for their development was at the beginning of the 20th century, with the efforts of Alexis Carrel to develop methods for prolonged in vitro tissue cultures.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Early studies in the 80's, led by Mina Bissell from the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, highlighted the importance of 3D techniques for creating accurate in vitro culturing models.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This work focused on the importance of the extracellular matrix and the ability of cultures in artificial 3D matrices to produce physiologically relevant multicellular structures, such as acinar structures in healthy and cancerous breast tissue models.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] These techniques have been applied to in vitro disease models used to evaluate cellular responses to pharmaceutical compounds.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Eric Simon, in a 1988 NIH SBIR grant report, showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale polystyrene and polycarbonate fibrous mats (now known as scaffolds) specifically intended for use as in vitro cell substrates.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This early use of electrospun fibrous lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types including Human Foreskin Fibroblasts (HFF), transformed Human Carcinoma (HEp-2), and Mink Lung Epithelium (MLE) would adhere to and proliferate upon the fibers.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] It was noted that as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more histotypic rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed in vivo.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] 3D cell culture, by emulating essential aspects of the in vivo environment, including interactions between cells and the extracellular matrix, allows for the faithful recreation of structural architecture and specialized functions in normal tissues or tumors in a laboratory setting.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This approach authentically models the conditions and processes of living tissues, producing responses akin to those observed in vivo.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Since its inception in the 1970s, 3D cell culture has provided significant insights into the mechanisms regulating tissue homeostasis and cancer.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, it has expedited translational research in the realms of cancer biology and tissue engineering.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] To date a major limiting factor in the size of constructs has been unprogrammed cell death called necrosis.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In living tissue, cells exist in 3D microenvironments with intricate cell-cell and cell-matrix interactions and complex transport dynamics for nutrients and cells.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Standard 2D, or monolayer, cell cultures are inadequate representations of this environment, which often makes them unreliable predictors of in vivo drug efficacy and toxicity.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] 3D spheroids more closely resemble in vivo tissue in terms of cellular communication and the development of extracellular matrices.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] These matrices help the cells to be able to move within their spheroid similar to the way cells would move in living tissue.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The spheroids are thus improved models for cell migration, differentiation, survival, and growth.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Furthermore, 3D cell cultures provide more accurate depiction of cell polarization, since in 2D, the cells can only be partially polarized.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, cells grown in 3D exhibit different gene expression than those grown in 2D.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The third dimension of cell growth provides more contact space for mechanical inputs and for cell adhesion, which is necessary for integrin ligation, cell contraction and even intracellular signalling.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] For the purposes of drug toxicology screening, it is much more useful to test gene expression of in vitro cells grown in 3D than 2D, since the gene expression of the 3D spheroids will more closely resemble gene expression in vivo.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Lastly, 3D cell cultures have greater stability and longer lifespans than cell cultures in 2D.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This means that they are more suitable for long-term studies and for demonstrating long-term effects of the drug.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] 3D environments also allow the cells to grow undisturbed.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In 2D, the cells must undergo regular trypsinization to provide them with sufficient nutrients for normal cell growth.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] 3D spheroids have been cultured in a lab setting for up to 302 days while still maintaining healthy, non-cancerous growth.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In the interdisciplinary research of biology and aerospace, the 3D printed-scaffolds are also being used for protecting cells from the effect of gravity during the launching.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] There are a large number of commercially available culturing tools that claim to provide the advantages of 3D cell culture.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In general, the platforms can be classified in two types of 3D culturing methods: **scaffold techniques** and **scaffold-free techniques**.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Scaffold techniques include the use of solid scaffolds, hydrogels and other materials.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In a recent study potentiality of human CD34+ stem cells explored by generating *in vitro* agarose gel 3D model to understand the bone ossification process.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Scaffolds can be used to generate microtissue 3D model by culturing fibroblasts outside of tumour cells, mimicking the tumor stroma interaction.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The effectiveness of scaffolds in various applications, particularly in tissue engineering, is significantly impacted by factors such as pore distribution, exposed surface area, and porosity.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The quantity and arrangement of these elements influence both the depth and rate at which cells penetrate the scaffold volume, the structure of the resulting extracellular matrix, and ultimately, the success of the regenerative process.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Scaffolds can be produced with diverse architectures depending on the manufacturing method, leading to either random or precisely designed pore distribution.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Recently, advanced computer-controlled rapid prototyping techniques have been employed to create scaffolds with well-organized geometries.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] As the natural extracellular matrix (ECM) is important in the survival, proliferation, differentiation and migration of the cells, different hydrogel matrices mimicking natural ECM structure are considered as potential approaches towards in vivo –like cell culturing.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Hydrogels are composed of interconnected pores with high water retention, which enables efficient transport of e.g. nutrients and gases.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Several different types of hydrogels from natural and synthetic materials are available for 3D cell culture, including e.g. animal ECM extract hydrogels, protein hydrogels, peptide hydrogels, polymer hydrogels, and wood-based nanocellulose hydrogel.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The approach to crafting the optimal ECM replica relies on the specific characteristics of the culture in question and typically involves employing diverse and independent chemical processes.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] For example, the utilization of photolabile chemistries can lead to the erosion of specific regions within a gel, and subsequently exposing these areas allows for the application of adhesive ligands, promoting cell adhesion and migration.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The development of more intricate frameworks is anticipated, comprising interwoven networks of chemistries under the control of both cells and users.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In essence, there is no singular network capable of faithfully emulating the intricate ECM of every tissue type.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] However, a thoughtful integration of bioinspired cues into synthetic gels holds the potential to yield resilient and versatile scaffolds applicable across various cell culture systems.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Scaffold free techniques employ another approach independent from the use scaffold.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Scaffold-free methods include e.g. the use of low adhesion plates, hanging drop plates, micropatterned surfaces, and rotating bioreactors, magnetic levitation, and magnetic 3D bioprinting.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids are a type of three-dimensional cell modeling that better simulate a live cell's environmental conditions compared to a two-dimensional cell model, specifically with the reactions between cells and the reactions between cells and the matrix.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Due to the strong interactions between the cells and the extracellular matrix in the spheroid, the permeability is limited, generating physiologically relevant gradients of e.g. nutrients and oxygen through the spheroid.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids are useful in the study of changing physiological characteristics of cells, the difference in the structure of healthy cells and tumor cells, and the changes cells undergo when forming a tumor.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids co-cultured with tumor and healthy cells were used to simulate how cancerous cells interact with normal cells.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids can also be co-cultured with fibroblasts to mimic tumor-stroma interaction.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids can be grown with a few different methods.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] One common method is to use low cell adhesion plates, typically a 96 well plate, to mass-produce spheroid cultures, where the aggregates form in the rounded bottom of the cell plates.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Spheroids can also be cultured using the hanging drop method involving forming cell aggregates in drops that hang from the surface of a cell plate.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Other methods under investigation include the use of rotating wall vessel bioreactors, which spins and cultures the cells when they are constantly in free fall and forms aggregates in layers Recently, some protocols have been standardized to produce uniform and reliable spheroids.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Researchers had also explored standardized, economical and reproducible methods for 3D cell culture.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] To improve reproducibility and transparency in spheroid experiments, an international consortium developed MISpheroID (Minimal Information in Spheroid Identity).
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] In the absence of blood vessels, oxygen permeability is impaired during necrotic nucleus formation and this prevents the ex vivo use of 3D cell culture.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] There is an emulsion template that can overcome this problem.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This approach allowed researchers to adjust the cell composition to attain the ideal conditions for promoting the synthesis of diverse angiogenic protein markers within the co-cultured clusteroids.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] HUVEC cells exhibit a reaction to the presence of Hep-G2 cells and their derivatives by generating endothelial cell sprouts in Matrigel, all without the external introduction of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) or other agents that induce angiogenesis.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The replication of this cultivation technique is straightforward for generating various cell co-culture spheroids.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The w/w Pickering emulsion template greatly aids in constructing 3D co-culture models, offering significant potential for applications in drug testing and tissue engineering.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The bioreactors used for 3D cell cultures are small plastic cylindrical chambers that are specifically engineered for the purpose of growing cells in three dimensions.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The bioreactor uses bioactive synthetic materials such as polyethylene terephthalate membranes to surround the spheroid cells in an environment that maintains high levels of nutrients.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] They are easy to open and close, so that cell spheroids can be removed for testing, yet the chamber is able to maintain 100% humidity throughout.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This humidity is important to achieve maximum cell growth and function.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The bioreactor chamber is part of a larger device that rotates to ensure equal cell growth in each direction across three dimensions.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] MC2 Biotek has developed a bioreactor to incubate proto-tissue that uses gas exchange to maintain high oxygen levels within the cell chamber.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This is an improvement over previous bioreactors because the higher oxygen levels help the cell grow and undergo normal cell respiration.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Collaborative efforts between tissue engineering (TE) firms, academic institutions, and industrial partners can enhance the transformation of research-oriented bioreactors into efficient commercial manufacturing systems.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Academic collaborators contribute foundational aspects, while industrial partners provide essential automation elements, ensuring compliance with regulatory standards and user-friendliness.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Established consortia in Europe, such as REMEDI, AUTOBONE, and STEPS, focus on developing automated systems to streamline the engineering of autologous cell-based grafts.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The aim is to meet regulatory criteria and ensure cost-effectiveness, making tissue-engineered products more clinically accessible and advancing the translational paradigm of TE from research to a competitive commercial field.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The utilization of microfluidic technology facilitates the generation of intricate micro-scale structures and the precise manipulation of parameters, thereby emulating the in vivo cellular milieu.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The integration of microfluidic technology with 3D cell culture holds considerable potential for applications that seek to replicate in vivo tissue characteristics, notably exemplified by the evolving organ-on-a-chip system.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The various cell structures in the human body must be vascularized to receive the nutrients and gas exchange in order to survive.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Similarly, 3D cell cultures in vitro require certain levels of fluid circulation, which can be problematic for dense, 3D cultures where cells may not all have adequate exposure to nutrients.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This is particularly important in hepatocyte cultures because the liver is a highly vascularized organ.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] One study cultured hepatocytes and vascular cells together on a collagen gel scaffold between microfluidic channels, and compared growth of cells in static and flowing environments, and showed the need for models with tissues and a microvascular network.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Another study showed that hanging-drop based spheroid co-culture device can be useful, generating two different cell spheroids on adjacent channels of microfluidic hanging drop device, and co-culturing spheroids with merging droplets, to monitor tumor-induced angiogenesis.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Microfluidic 3D cell culture, with its potential applications in biomedical research and tissue engineering, is an area of growing interest.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] However, its advancement is accompanied by several formidable challenges.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] One such challenge pertains to the difficulty in accessing cultured cells within microsystems, coupled with the intricate nature of sample extraction for subsequent assays.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Additionally, the development of methodologies and devices dedicated to in vivo-like cell metabolism and functions study, as well as drug discovery, represents a significant hurdle for microfluidic 3D cell culture devices.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Another noteworthy impediment is the limited availability of microfabrication instrumentation in conventional biology laboratories.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, the commercialization of mature and user-friendly microfluidic devices poses a substantial challenge, hindering their accessibility to biologists.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Lastly, while biologists often seek high-throughput assay tools with optimal reproducibility, microfluidics encounters technical limitations in meeting these demands, despite the potential feasibility of parallel assays.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Advanced development of 3D models for high-throughput screening in high density formats has recently been achievable due to technological achievements related to increased microplate density.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] These can be found in 384 and 1536-well formats that are cell repellent, cost effective, and amenable to fully automated screening platforms.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Two options that afford 1536-well formats are available from either Greiner Bio-One using the m3D Magnetic 3D bioprinting and Corning Life Sciences which incorporates an ultra-low attachment surface coating, along with a microcavity geometry and gravity to create 3D models.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Due to the rapid and affordable methods and technologies that have been developed for 3D screening, parallel high-throughput screening approaches to test isogenic pairs of oncogene related mutants versus wildtype have been enabled.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Moreover, High-throughput screening techniques play a pivotal role in connecting the realms of pharmacology and toxicology within the framework of 3D cell culture.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] A primary purpose of growing cells in 3D scaffolds and as 3D cell spheroids in vitro is to test pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic effects of drugs and nanomaterials in preclinical trials.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Toxicology studies have shown 3D cell cultures to be nearly on par with in vivo studies for the purposes of testing toxicity of drug compounds.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] When comparing LD50 values for 6 common drugs: acetaminophen, amiodarone, diclofenac, metformin, phenformin, and valproic acid, the 3D spheroid values correlated directly with those from in vivo studies.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Although 2D cell cultures have previously been used to test for toxicity along with in vivo studies, the 3D spheroids are better at testing chronic exposure toxicity because of their longer life spans.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The matrix in 3D Spheroids causes cells to maintain actin filaments and is more relevant physiologically in cytoskeletal organization and cell polarity and shape of human cells.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The three-dimensional arrangement allows the cultures to provide a model that more accurately resembles human tissue in vivo without using animal test subjects.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The current protocols for evaluating drug candidates and assessing toxicity heavily depend on outcomes derived from early-stage in vitro cell-based assays, with the expectation that these assays faithfully capture critical aspects of in vivo pharmacology and toxicology.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Innovative approaches to multiplexed cell-based assay designs, involving the selection of specific cell types, signaling pathways, and reporters, have become standard practice.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Despite these advancements, a considerable percentage of new chemical and biological entities (NCEs/NBEs) encounter setbacks in late-stage human drug testing.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Some receive regulatory "black box" warnings, while others are withdrawn from the market due to safety concerns post-regulatory approval.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] This recurrent pattern underscores the inadequacy of in vitro cell-based assays and subsequent preclinical in vivo studies in furnishing comprehensive pharmacological and toxicity data or reliable predictive capacity for comprehending the in vivo performance of drug candidates.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The absence of a dependable translational assay toolkit for pharmacology and toxicology contributes to the high cost and inefficiency of transitioning from initial in vitro cell-based screens to in vivo testing and subsequent clinical approvals.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Particular emphasis is placed on their capacity to retain essential cell and molecular interactions, as well as physiological parameters influencing cell phenotypes and responses to bioactive agents.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] The distinctive advantages and challenges associated with these models are scrutinized, with a specific focus on their suitability for cell-based assays and their predictive capabilities, crucial for establishing accurate correlations with in vivo mechanisms of drug toxicity.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] While assessing safety and efficacy, these models are well equipped to model a wide range of disease states.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Each of these models has advantages and limitations that require model development and data interpretation.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Public-private partnerships are critical to advance and stimulate research in this area.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Existing 3D methods are not without limitations, including scalability, reproducibility, sensitivity, and compatibility with high-throughput screening (HTS) instruments.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Cell-based HTS relies on rapid determination of cellular response to drug interaction, such as dose dependent cell viability, cell-cell/cell-matrix interaction, and/or cell migration, but the available assays are not optimized for 3D cell culturing.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Another challenge faced by 3D cell culturing is the limited amount of data and publications that address mechanisms and correlations of drug interaction, cell differentiation, and cell-signalling in these 3D environments.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] None of the 3D methods have yet replaced 2D culturing on a large scale, including in the drug development process; although the number of 3D cell culturing publications is increasing rapidly, the current limited biochemical characterization of 3D tissue diminishes the adoption of new methods.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] There are also problems using spheroids as a model for cancerous tissue.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Tissue engineering requires 3D cellular scaffolds.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] As biomaterials, various natural and synthetic polymer hydrogels have been used by scientists to design 3D scaffolds.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Since this barrier is a structure that mimics the natural ECM microenvironment, synthetic scaffolds may be more useful for studying specific tumorigenic steps.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culture] Finally, it is suggested that the most suitable three-dimensional models should be carefully selected according to specific targets.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The **Magnetic Levitation** **Method** (MLM) is a technique for growing 3D cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] In this approach, cells are treated with magnetic nanoparticles and exposed to spatially varying magnetic fields produced by neodymium magnetic drivers.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The process causes cells to levitate to the air-liquid interface within a standard petri dish.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The magnetic nanoparticle assemblies consist of magnetic iron oxide nanoparticles, gold nanoparticles, and cell-adhesive peptide sequences.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] This method can be applied to cultures with five hundred to millions of cells and is adaptable for use in single-dish systems as well as high-throughput, low-volume systems.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Additionally, magnetized cells can be utilized as building blocks for magnetic 3D bioprinting.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] 3D cell culture methods have been developed to enable research into the behavior of cells in an environment that represents their interactions in-vivo more accurately.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] 3D cell culturing by magnetic levitation uses biocompatible polymer-based reagents to deliver magnetic nanoparticles to individual cells, so that an applied magnetic driver can levitate cells off the bottom of the cell culture dish, rapidly bringing cells together near the air-liquid interface.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] This act initiates cell-cell interactions in the absence of any artificial surface or matrix.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Magnetic fields are designed to form 3D multicellular structures, including the expression of extracellular matrix proteins.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The matrix, protein expression, and response to exogenous agents of the resulting tissue show similarity to in-vivo results.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] 3D cell culturing by magnetic levitation method (MLM) was developed with collaboration between scientists at Rice University and University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center in 2008.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] 3D cell culturing technology was later licensed and commercialized by Nano3D Biosciences.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The mechanism of the magnetic levitation model in 3D cell culturing combines various techniques within the frame of nanobiotechnology.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] One approach to the process is described below.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] At the beginning of the process, magnetite nanoparticles are added, then dispersed uniformly throughout the cell culture.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] After the cell culture containing the nanoparticles has been allowed to incubate, it is moved to a petri dish, and a magnetic drive is placed on top of the petri dish.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] When an external magnetic field is applied through the drive, it causes the cell culture mixture, still containing the magnetic nanoparticles, to levitate within the petri dish.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The levitation results in immediate cell-cell interaction.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] After the mixture disperses and stretches, there is gradual formation of 3D structures that are visible after about 4 hours.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The magnetic iron oxide nanoparticles are described as the "nanoshuttle", in which their magnetic properties allows the cells to rise within the culture they are added to due to the external magnetic field, thus "shuttling".
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Patterns of protein expression in levitated cultures resemble the patterns observed *in-vivo*.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The transmembrane protein N-cadherin is often used as an indicator of in-vivo-like tissue assembly in 3D culturing.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Referring to the figure, in the mouse and levitated culture (left and middle image), N-cadherin is clearly concentrated in the membrane, and also present in cytoplasm and cell junctions, whereas the 2D system (right image) shows N-cadherin in the cytoplasm and nucleus, but absent from the membrane.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] One of the challenges of in vitro modelling of complex tissues is the difficulty of co-culturing different cell types.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Co-culturing of different cell types can be achieved at the onset of levitation, either by mixing different cell types before levitation, or by magnetically guiding 3D cultures in an invasion assay format.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Co-culturing in a realistic tissue architecture is important for accurately modeling in-vivo conditions.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] One example is increasing the accuracy of cellular assays, as shown in the figure on the right.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] In the figure, the human GBM cells and normal human astrocytes (NHA) are cultured separately and then magnetically guided together (left, time 0).
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Invasion of GBM into NHA in 3D culture provides an assay for basic cancer biology and drug screening (right, 12h to 252h).
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Magnetic levitation has shown potential for maintaining cell viability and simulating in vivo conditions.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] However, its scalability and efficacy in comparison to traditional culturing methods have been topics of discussion.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] By facilitating the assembly of different populations of cells using the MLM, consistent generation of organoids, termed adipospheres, capable of simulating the complex intercellular interactions of endogenous white adipose tissue (WAT) can be achieved.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Co-culturing 3T3-L1 preadipocytes in a 3D space with murine endothelial bEND.3 cells can create a vascular-like network assembly with concomitant lipogenesis in perivascular cells (refer to the attached figure).
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] In addition to cell lines, organogenesis of white adipose tissue (WAT) can be simulated from primary cells.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Adipocyte-depleted stromal vascular fraction (SVF) containing adipose stromal cells (ASC), endothelial cells, and infiltrating leukocytes derived from mouse WAT were cultured in 3D.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] This revealed organoids striking in hierarchical organization with distinct capsules and internal large vessel-like structures lined with endothelial cells, as well as perivascular localization of ASC.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Upon adipogenesis induction of either 3T3-L1 adipospheres or adipospheres derived from SVF, the cells efficiently formed large lipid droplets typical of white adipocytes in-vivo, whereas only smaller lipid droplet formation is achievable in 2D.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] This indicates intercellular signalling that better recapitulates WAT organogenesis.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] This MLM for 3D co-culturing creates a liposphere appropriate for WAT modeling *ex vivo* and provides a new platform for functional screens to identify molecules bioactive toward individual adipose cell populations.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] It can also be adopted for WAT transplantation applications and aid other approaches to WAT-based cell therapy.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] The use of additional manipulation tools may be needed to organize 3D co-cultures into a configuration similar enough to native tissue architecture.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Endothelial cells (PEC), smooth muscle cells (SMC), fibroblasts (PF), and epithelial cells (EpiC) cultured through magnetic levitation can be sequentially layered in a drag-and-drop manner to create bronchioles that maintain phenotype and induce extracellular matrix formation.
[src:cell-culture/3d-cell-culturing-by-magnetic-levitation] Below is a list of cell types (primary and cell lines) that have been successfully cultured by the magnetic levitation method.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The 3T3-L1 cell line is a sub clone that was initially developed from a mouse embryo, from a clonal expansion of Swiss 3T3 cells.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] In 1962, the original 3T3 cell line that it was established by George Todaro and Howard Green of the New York University School of Medicine.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The original cell line was developed through the 3T3 process, which is where the cells derive their naming nomenclature.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The 3T3 process began with cultures having 3 days to propagate on a plate (the first "3"), and then a transfer (the "T") of 300,000 cells (second "3") to a new plate to restart the process.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] These cells will be identified as 3T3 only after they are taken through 20 to 30 passages and have established at a stable growth rate.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] These cells were originally used to study the properties of transformed cells and the mechanisms of neoplastic transformation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] In 1971, Green and Kehinde established a subline of 3T3 cells, called 3T3-L1, which demonstrated a greater propensity for differentiation into adipocytes and a higher affinity for lipid deposition.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The cells were cultured in a serum-containing medium and demonstrated a fibroblast-like morphology.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] In the early 1980s, it was discovered that these cells could be induced to differentiate into adipocytes in response to hormonal stimulation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] 3T3-L1 cells, similar to their other 3T3 counterparts, are typically propagated as an adherent monolayer within a culture vessel.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Basal cell culture medias for 3T3-L1 cells tends to contain a version of Dubelcco's Modified Eagle's Medium (DMEM), fetal bovine serum (FBS), and an antibiotic at specific levels dependent upon protocol.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The DMEM provides essential nutrients, while the FBS provides vital growth factors, and the antibiotic protects against culture contamination.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The process of adipogenesis, and the start of differentiation can be induced in 3T3-L1 cells through the addition of compounds such as a synthetic glucocorticoid, a phosphodiesterase inhibitor, and insulin.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The most commonly used synthetic glucocorticoid in adipocyte differentiation procedures tends to be dexamethasone and the most commonly used phosphodiesterase inhibitor is 1-methyl-3-isobutyl-xanthine (IBMX).
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] These compounds are usually used in varying combinations and concentrations in differentiation media dependent upon the protocol utilized.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] 3T3-L1 cells are commonly utilized as an effective model for white adipocytes because of their similar fibroblast-like morphology, lipid accumulation, gene expression, and basal energy exchanges and transformations.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Although, some literature suggests that 3T3-L1 adipocytes can possess certain phenotypic signatures similar to other adipocyte lineages aside from white adipocytes.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Adipogenesis can be described as the effective differentiation of preadipocytes into mature adipocytes that can then undergo lipogenesis.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] During this period, cells can undergo hyperplastic growth until they are differentiated.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Since 3T3-L1 cells are an immortalized cell line and require a hormonal differentiation, there has been much debate on their comparability to *in vivo* studies and primary cell lines.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Aside from the synthetic differentiation itself, 3T3-L1 lineages can display low differentiation efficiency when utilizing common differentiation methods.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Low differentiation efficiency can change adipogenesis and lipogenesis related experiment results and limit result interpretation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Studies suggest that differentiation efficiency can rely on factors such as culture dish material, culture dish provider, culture dish type, cell confluence at the time of differentiation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Lipogenesis can be described as the biochemical and physical accumulation of triacylglycerides in a differentiated adipocyte.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Again, the deposition of adipose tissue relies on the number of adipocytes, their differentiation efficiency and overall lipid accumulation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] It is not unrelated that the inhibition of one of these processes could impact others as well.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] One advantage of using 3T3-L1 cells is their well-characterized differentiation process, which allows for reproducible experiments and comparison of results across studies.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Additionally, the cells can be easily cultured and maintained in the laboratory, and are relatively inexpensive compared to other cell lines or animal models.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] However, one limitation of using 3T3-L1 cells is that they are derived from mice and may not fully recapitulate human biology.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Additionally, 3T3-L1 cells are a homogeneous cell population, which may not fully reflect the heterogeneity of adipose tissue in vivo.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] These limitations can affect comparability of this particular cell lineage.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] While 3T3-L1 gene expression mimics that of a white adipocyte, some literature suggests some phenotypic 3T3-L1 characteristics can resemble that of brown adipocytes.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] 3T3-L1 cells, when supplemented with catecholamines, utilized UCP-1 to increase oxygen consumption similar to brown adipocytes.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] This brown adipocyte characteristic was only enhanced with long-term catecholamine supplementation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] While the 3T3-L1 lineage can display characteristics similar to both white and brown adipocytes, they have had different results in relation to beige adipocyte phenotypecharacteristics.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] When 3T3-L1 cells are differentiated into beige adipocytes, they fail to express any beige phenotypic signatures.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] The process of differentiation is constantly being re-evaluated in the adipose research sector.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] While a majority of *in vitro* experiments utilize the common insulin, dexamethasone, and IBMX combinations, others have found other methods of differentiating and inducing the process of adipogenesis.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Other methods can include transfection with a *ras* oncogene, the combination of dexamethasone and octanoate, and the normal combination with the addition of a peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor y (PPARy) agonist.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] While some protocols promote the process of adipogenesis in 3T3-L1 cells, others reduce or inhibit the process.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] In 3T3-L1 adipocytes, oleanolic acid (5*u*mol/L) down regulated the expression of PPARy and cytidine-cytidine-adenosine-adenosine-thymidine (CCAAT) enhancer binding protein *a* (C/EBP*a*) during differentiation.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Thus, oleanolic acid suppressed adipocyte differentiation and consequential lipid accumulation when applied in differentiation media to 3T3-L1 cells.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Berberine impacted GATA-2 and GATA-3 and thus inhibited 3T3-L1 differentiation when applied during differentiation or post-differentiation *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Long term treatment of flavonoid, luteolin, affected PPARy activation and suppressed adipogenesis 3T3-L1 adipocytes.
[src:cell-culture/3t3-l1] Isopanduratin A also inhibited adipogenesis in 3T3-L1 adipocytes by impacting multiple targets in the adipogenic growth cycle such as PPARy, C/EBP*a*, sterol regulatory binding protein- 1c (SREB-1c), adiponectin, and lipoprotein lipase(LPL).
[src:cell-culture/4t1] 4T1 cell line was originally isolated by Fred Miller and colleagues as one of four sublines derived from the 410.4 tumor that was isolated from a single spontaneously arising mammary tumor.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] 4T1 resembles human metastatic triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) in lack of the expression of estrogen receptor (ER), progesterone receptor (PR), and epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2).
[src:cell-culture/4t1] In addition, it was described, that this cell line is poorly immunogenic in mice, which corresponds to the characteristics of human mammary adenocarcinoma and leads to the higher tumorigenicity and invasiveness of this breast cancer model.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] To understand the pathogenesis of cancer patients, it is necessary to have model systems that faithfully mimic this condition.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] The application of a murine cancer cell line, such as 4T1, in a mouse model is of great value for preclinical TNBC studies.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] The 4T1 cell line is widely used as a syngeneic model for human triple-negative breast cancer, which is responsible for more than 17% of breast cancers diagnosed worldwide each year.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] 4T1 cells can be transplanted into the fat pad of the murine mammary gland, where they are highly tumorigenic, invasive, and spontaneously metastasize to distant organs such as the lungs, liver, lymph nodes, brain, and bone.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] 4T1 cells grow in 37 °C with 95% air and 5% of carbon dioxide (CO 2).
[src:cell-culture/4t1] Their average doubling time is 14 hours.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] The base medium for this cell line is RPMI-1640 Medium with a fetal bovine serum in a final concentration of 10%.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] 4T1 cells should not be allowed to become 100% confluent.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] Subculturing at 80% confluence is recommended.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] For detaching the cells from the surface, rinsing with 0.25% trypsin-0.53mM EDTA solution at room temperature is used.
[src:cell-culture/4t1] Complete growth medium 95% with DMSO 5% is used as a freezing medium and cells are stored at liquid nitrogen vapor phase temperature.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] A431 cells were established from an epidermoid carcinoma in the skin (epidermis) of an 85- year-old female patient.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] Epidermal growth factor (EGF) stimulation of A431 cells induces rapid tyrosine phosphorylation of intracellular signaling proteins which control cellular processes such as growth, proliferation and apoptosis.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] At low (picomolar) concentrations, EGF promotes cell growth of A431 cells whereas at higher (nanomolar) concentrations it inhibits growth by causing the cells to terminally differentiate.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] Treatment of A431 cells with bradykinin reduces basal and EGF-induced EGFR phosphorylation.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] Treatment with Sertoli cell secreted growth factor (SCSGF) strongly induces cell proliferation.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] Stimulation of A431 cells with phorbol esters induces expression of interleukin 1-related protein IL1H.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] A431 cells are used in studies of the cell cycle and cancer-associated cell signalling pathways since they express abnormally high levels of the Epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR).
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] They are often used as a positive control for EGFR expression.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] They contain no functional p53, a potent tumor suppressor gene, and are highly sensitive to mitogenic stimuli.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] In xenografts, A431 cells have shown antitumorigenic properties of introduced EGF and related radiation sensitization characteristics.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] Other *in vitro* studies have found EGF to also cause substantial lowering of DNA replication and protein synthesis.
[src:cell-culture/a431-cells] The A431 lines engineered to express tumor antigens such as mesothelin and GPC3 have been made as cell models to test cancer therapeutics.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In practice, the term "cell culture" now refers to the culturing of cells derived from multicellular eukaryotes, especially animal cells, in contrast with other types of culture that also grow cells, such as plant tissue culture, fungal culture, and microbiological culture (of microbes).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The historical development and methods of cell culture are closely interrelated with those of tissue culture and organ culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Viral culture is also related, with cells as hosts for the viruses.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The laboratory technique of maintaining live cell lines (a population of cells descended from a single cell and containing the same genetic makeup) separated from their original tissue source became more robust in the middle 20th century.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The 19th-century English physiologist Sydney Ringer developed salt solutions containing the chlorides of sodium, potassium, calcium and magnesium suitable for maintaining the beating of an isolated animal heart outside the body.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In 1885 Wilhelm Roux removed a section of the medullary plate of an embryonic chicken and maintained it in a warm saline solution for several days, establishing the basic principle of tissue culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In 1907 the zoologist Ross Granville Harrison demonstrated the growth of frog embryonic cells that would give rise to nerve cells in a medium of clotted lymph.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Lambert grew vaccinia virus in fragments of guinea pig corneal tissue.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In 1996, the first use of regenerative tissue was used to replace a small length of urethra, which led to the understanding that the technique of obtaining samples of tissue, growing it outside the body without a scaffold, and reapplying it, can be used for only small distances of less than 1 cm.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Ross Granville Harrison, working at Johns Hopkins Medical School and then at Yale University, published results of his experiments from 1907 to 1910, establishing the methodology of tissue culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Gottlieb Haberlandt first pointed out the possibilities of the culture of isolated tissues, plant tissue culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] He suggested that the potentialities of individual cells via tissue culture as well as that the reciprocal influences of tissues on one another could be determined by this method.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Since Haberlandt's original assertions, methods for tissue and cell culture have been realized, leading to significant discoveries in biology and medicine.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] He presented his original idea of *totipotentiality* in 1902, stating that "Theoretically all plant cells are able to give rise to a complete plant." The term *tissue culture* was coined by American pathologist Montrose Thomas Burrows.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell culture techniques were advanced significantly in the 1940s and 1950s to support research in virology.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Growing viruses in cell cultures allowed preparation of purified viruses for the manufacture of vaccines.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The injectable polio vaccine developed by Jonas Salk was one of the first products mass-produced using cell culture techniques.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This vaccine was made possible by the cell culture research of John Franklin Enders, Thomas Huckle Weller, and Frederick Chapman Robbins, who were awarded a Nobel Prize for their discovery of a method of growing the virus in monkey kidney cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell culture has contributed to the development of vaccines for many diseases.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In modern usage, "tissue culture" generally refers to the growth of cells from a tissue from a multicellular organism *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] These cells may be cells isolated from a donor organism (primary cells) or an immortalised cell line.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The cells are bathed in a culture medium, which contains essential nutrients and energy sources necessary for the cells' survival.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Thus, in its broader sense, "tissue culture" is often used interchangeably with "cell culture".
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] On the other hand, the strict meaning of "tissue culture" refers to the culturing of tissue pieces, i.e. explant culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Tissue culture is an important tool for the study of the biology of cells from multicellular organisms.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It provides an *in vitro* model of the tissue in a well defined environment which can be easily manipulated and analysed.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In animal tissue culture, cells may be grown as two-dimensional monolayers (conventional culture) or within fibrous scaffolds or gels to attain more naturalistic three-dimensional tissue-like structures (3D culture).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A 1988 NIH SBIR grant report showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale polymeric fibrous scaffolds specifically intended for use as *in vitro* cell and tissue substrates.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This early use of electrospun fibrous lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types would adhere to and proliferate upon polycarbonate fibers.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It was noted that as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed of tissues *in vivo*.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Plant tissue culture in particular is concerned with the growing of entire plants from small pieces of plant tissue, cultured in medium.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells can be isolated from tissues for *ex vivo* culture in several ways.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells can be easily purified from blood; however, only the white cells are capable of growth in culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells can be isolated from solid tissues by digesting the extracellular matrix using enzymes such as collagenase, trypsin, or pronase, before agitating the tissue to release the cells into suspension.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Alternatively, pieces of tissue can be placed in growth media, and the cells that grow out are available for culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This method is known as explant culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells that are cultured directly from a subject are known as primary cells.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] With the exception of some derived from tumors, most primary cell cultures have limited lifespan.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] An established or immortalized cell line has acquired the ability to proliferate indefinitely either through random mutation or deliberate modification, such as artificial expression of the telomerase gene.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Numerous cell lines are well established as representative of particular cell types.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] For the majority of isolated primary cells, they undergo the process of senescence and stop dividing after a certain number of population doublings while generally retaining their viability (described as the Hayflick limit).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Aside from temperature and gas mixture, the most commonly varied factor in culture systems is the cell growth medium.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Recipes for growth media can vary in pH, glucose concentration, growth factors, and the presence of other nutrients.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The growth factors used to supplement media are often derived from the serum of animal blood, such as fetal bovine serum (FBS), bovine calf serum, equine serum, and porcine serum.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] One complication of these blood-derived ingredients is the potential for contamination of the culture with viruses or prions, particularly in medical biotechnology applications.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Current practice is to minimize or eliminate the use of these ingredients wherever possible and use human platelet lysate (hPL).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This eliminates the worry of cross-species contamination when using FBS with human cells. hPL has emerged as a safe and reliable alternative as a direct replacement for FBS or other animal serum.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In addition, chemically defined media can be used to eliminate any serum trace (human or animal), but this cannot always be accomplished with different cell types.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Alternative strategies involve sourcing the animal blood from countries with minimum BSE/TSE risk, such as The United States, Australia and New Zealand, and using purified nutrient concentrates derived from serum in place of whole animal serum for cell culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Plating density (number of cells per volume of culture medium) plays a critical role for some cell types.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] For example, a lower plating density makes granulosa cells exhibit estrogen production, while a higher plating density makes them appear as progesterone-producing theca lutein cells.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells can be grown either in suspension or **adherent cultures**.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Some cells naturally live in suspension, without being attached to a surface, such as cells that exist in the bloodstream.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] There are also cell lines that have been modified to be able to survive in suspension cultures so they can be grown to a higher density than adherent conditions would allow.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Adherent cells require a surface, such as tissue culture plastic or microcarrier, which may be coated with extracellular matrix (such as collagen and laminin) components to increase adhesion properties and provide other signals needed for growth and differentiation.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Most cells derived from solid tissues are adherent.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Another type of adherent culture is **organotypic culture**, which involves growing cells in a three-dimensional (3-D) environment as opposed to two-dimensional culture dishes.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This 3D culture system is biochemically and physiologically more similar to *in vivo* tissue, but is technically challenging to maintain because of many factors (e.g. diffusion).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell line cross-contamination can be a problem for scientists working with cultured cells.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Studies suggest anywhere from 15 to 20% of the time, cells used in experiments have been misidentified or contaminated with another cell line.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Problems with cell line cross-contamination have even been detected in lines from the NCI-60 panel, which are used routinely for drug-screening studies.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Major cell line repositories, including the American Type Culture Collection (ATCC), the European Collection of Cell Cultures (ECACC) and the German Collection of Microorganisms and Cell Cultures (DSMZ), have received cell line submissions from researchers that were misidentified by them.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Such contamination poses a problem for the quality of research produced using cell culture lines, and the major repositories are now authenticating all cell line submissions.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] ATCC uses short tandem repeat (STR) DNA fingerprinting to authenticate its cell lines.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] To address this problem of cell line cross-contamination, researchers are encouraged to authenticate their cell lines at an early passage to establish the identity of the cell line.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Authentication should be repeated before freezing cell line stocks, every two months during active culturing and before any publication of research data generated using the cell lines.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Many methods are used to identify cell lines, including isoenzyme analysis, human lymphocyte antigen (HLA) typing, chromosomal analysis, karyotyping, morphology and STR analysis.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] One significant cell-line cross contaminant is the immortal HeLa cell line.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] HeLa contamination was first noted in the early 1960s in non-human culture in the USA.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Intraspecies contamination was discovered in nineteen cell lines in the seventies.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In 1974, five human cell lines from the Soviet Union were found to be HeLa.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A follow-up study analysing 50-odd cell lines indicated that half had HeLa markers, but contaminant HeLa had hybridised with the original cell lines.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] HeLa cell contamination from air droplets has been reported.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] HeLa was even unknowingly injected into human subjects by Jonas Salk in a 1978 vaccine trial.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] As cells generally continue to divide in culture, they generally grow to fill the available area or volume.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The choice of culture medium might affect the physiological relevance of findings from cell culture experiments due to the differences in the nutrient composition and concentrations.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A systematic bias in generated datasets was recently shown for CRISPR and RNAi gene silencing screens, and for metabolic profiling of cancer cell lines.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Using a growth medium that better represents the physiological levels of nutrients can improve the physiological relevance of in vitro studies and recently such media types, as Plasmax and Human Plasma Like Medium (HPLM), were developed.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Among the common manipulations carried out on culture cells are media changes, passaging cells, and transfecting cells.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] These are generally performed using tissue culture methods that rely on aseptic technique.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Aseptic technique aims to avoid contamination with bacteria, yeast, or other cell lines.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Manipulations are typically carried out in a biosafety cabinet or laminar flow cabinet to exclude contaminating micro-organisms.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Antibiotics (e.g. penicillin and streptomycin) and antifungals (e.g.amphotericin B and Antibiotic-Antimycotic solution) can also be added to the growth media.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] As cells undergo metabolic processes, acid is produced and the pH decreases.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Often, a pH indicator is added to the medium to measure nutrient depletion.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In the case of adherent cultures, the media can be removed directly by aspiration, and then is replaced.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Media changes in non-adherent cultures involve centrifuging the culture and resuspending the cells in fresh media.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Passaging (also known as subculture or splitting cells) involves transferring a small number of cells into a new vessel.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells can be cultured for a longer time if they are split regularly, as it avoids the senescence associated with prolonged high cell density.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Suspension cultures are easily passaged with a small amount of culture containing a few cells diluted in a larger volume of fresh media.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] For adherent cultures, cells first need to be detached; this is commonly done with a mixture of trypsin-EDTA; however, other enzyme mixes are now available for this purpose.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A small number of detached cells can then be used to seed a new culture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Some cell cultures, such as RAW cells are mechanically scraped from the surface of their vessel with rubber scrapers.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Another common method for manipulating cells involves the introduction of foreign DNA by transfection.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This is often performed to cause cells to express a gene of interest.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] More recently, the transfection of RNAi constructs have been realized as a convenient mechanism for suppressing the expression of a particular gene/protein.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] DNA can also be inserted into cells using viruses, in methods referred to as transduction, infection or transformation.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Viruses, as parasitic agents, are well suited to introducing DNA into cells, as this is a part of their normal course of reproduction.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell lines that originate with humans have been somewhat controversial in bioethics, as they may outlive their parent organism and later be used in the discovery of lucrative medical treatments.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In the pioneering decision in this area, the Supreme Court of California held in *Moore v.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Regents of the University of California* that human patients have no property rights in cell lines derived from organs removed with their consent.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It is possible to fuse normal cells with an immortalised cell line.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This method is used to produce monoclonal antibodies.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In brief, lymphocytes isolated from the spleen (or possibly blood) of an immunised animal are combined with an immortal myeloma cell line (B cell lineage) to produce a hybridoma which has the antibody specificity of the primary lymphocyte and the immortality of the myeloma.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Selective growth medium (HA or HAT) is used to select against unfused myeloma cells; primary lymphoctyes die quickly in culture and only the fused cells survive.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] These are screened for production of the required antibody, generally in pools to start with and then after single cloning.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A cell strain is derived either from a primary culture or a cell line by the selection or cloning of cells having specific properties or characteristics which must be defined.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell strains are cells that have been adapted to culture but, unlike cell lines, have a finite division potential.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Non-immortalized cells stop dividing after 40 to 60 population doublings and, after this, they lose their ability to proliferate (a genetically determined event known as senescence).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Mass culture of animal cell lines is fundamental to the manufacture of viral vaccines and other products of biotechnology.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Culture of human stem cells is used to expand the number of cells and differentiate the cells into various somatic cell types for transplantation.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Stem cell culture is also used to harvest the molecules and exosomes that the stem cells release for the purposes of therapeutic development.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Biological products produced by recombinant DNA (rDNA) technology in animal cell cultures include enzymes, synthetic hormones, immunobiologicals (monoclonal antibodies, interleukins, lymphokines), and anticancer agents.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Although many simpler proteins can be produced using rDNA in bacterial cultures, more complex proteins that are glycosylated (carbohydrate-modified) currently must be made in animal cells.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Mammalian cells ensure expressed proteins are folded correctly and possess human-like glycosylation and post-translational modifications.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] An important example of such a complex protein is the hormone erythropoietin.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It also offers to confirm single cell origin of somatic embryos and the asymmetry of the first cell division, which starts the process.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell culture is also a key technique for cellular agriculture, which aims to provide both new products and new ways of producing existing agricultural products like milk, (cultured) meat, fragrances, and rhino horn from cells and microorganisms.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It is therefore considered one means of achieving animal-free agriculture.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It is also a central tool for teaching cell biology.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Research in tissue engineering, stem cells and molecular biology primarily involves cultures of cells on flat plastic dishes.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This technique is known as two-dimensional (2D) cell culture, and was first developed by Wilhelm Roux who, in 1885, removed a portion of the medullary plate of an embryonic chicken and maintained it in warm saline for several days on a flat glass plate.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] From the advance of polymer technology arose today's standard plastic dish for 2D cell culture, commonly known as the Petri dish.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Julius Richard Petri, a German bacteriologist, is generally credited with this invention while working as an assistant to Robert Koch.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Various researchers today also utilize culturing laboratory flasks, conicals, and even disposable bags like those used in single-use bioreactors.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Aside from Petri dishes, scientists have long been growing cells within biologically derived matrices such as collagen or fibrin, and more recently, on synthetic hydrogels such as polyacrylamide or PEG.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] They do this in order to elicit phenotypes that are not expressed on conventionally rigid substrates.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell culture in three dimensions has been touted as "Biology's New Dimension".
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] At present, the practice of cell culture remains based on varying combinations of single or multiple cell structures in 2D.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Currently, there is an increase in use of 3D cell cultures in research areas including drug discovery, cancer biology, regenerative medicine, nanomaterials assessment and basic life science research.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] 3D cell cultures can be grown using a scaffold or matrix, or in a scaffold-free manner.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Scaffold based cultures utilize an acellular 3D matrix or a liquid matrix.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Scaffold-free methods are normally generated in suspensions.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Culturing cells in 3D leads to wide variation in gene expression signatures and partly mimics tissues in the physiological states.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A 3D cell culture model showed cell growth similar to that of in vivo than did a monolayer culture, and all three cultures were capable of sustaining cell growth.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] As 3D culturing has been developed it turns out to have a great potential to design tumors models and investigate malignant transformation and metastasis, 3D cultures can provide aggerate tool for understanding changes, interactions, and cellular signaling.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Eric Simon, in a 1988 NIH SBIR grant report, showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale polystyrene and polycarbonate fibrous scaffolds specifically intended for use as *in vitro* cell substrates.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] This early use of electrospun fibrous lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types including Human Foreskin Fibroblasts (HFF), transformed Human Carcinoma (HEp-2), and Mink Lung Epithelium (MLE) would adhere to and proliferate upon polycarbonate fibers.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] It was noted that, as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more histotypic rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed *in vivo*.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] As the natural extracellular matrix (ECM) is important in the survival, proliferation, differentiation and migration of cells, different hydrogel culture matrices mimicking natural ECM structure are seen as potential approaches to in vivo–like cell culturing.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Hydrogels are composed of interconnected pores with high water retention, which enables efficient transport of substances such as nutrients and gases.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Several different types of hydrogels from natural and synthetic materials are available for 3D cell culture, including animal ECM extract hydrogels, protein hydrogels, peptide hydrogels, polymer hydrogels, and wood-based nanocellulose hydrogel.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The magnetic nanoparticle assemblies consist of magnetic iron oxide nanoparticles, gold nanoparticles, and the polymer polylysine.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] 3D cell culturing is scalable, with the capability for culturing 500 cells to millions of cells or from single dish to high-throughput low volume systems.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell culture is a fundamental component of tissue culture and tissue engineering, as it establishes the basics of growing and maintaining cells *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The major application of human cell culture is in stem cell industry, where mesenchymal stem cells are isolated, cultured, and subjected to long-term storage via optimized cryopreservation, so as to retain stable differentiation and immunomodulatory properties post-thaw for future applications.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Tissue engineering potentially offers dramatic improvements in low cost medical care for hundreds of thousands of patients annually.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Vaccines for polio, measles, mumps, rubella, and chickenpox are currently made in cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Due to the H5N1 pandemic threat, research into using cell culture for influenza vaccines is being funded by the United States government.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Novel ideas in the field include recombinant DNA-based vaccines, such as one made using human adenovirus (a common cold virus) as a vector, and novel adjuvants.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The technique of co-culturing is used to study cell crosstalk between two or more types of cells on a plate or in a 3D matrix.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The cultivation of different stem cells and the interaction of immune cells can be investigated in an in vitro model similar to biological tissue.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Since most tissues contain more than one type of cell, it is important to evaluate their interaction in a 3D culture environment to gain a better understanding of their interaction and to introduce mimetic tissues.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] There are two types of co-culturing: direct and indirect.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] While direct interaction involves cells being in direct contact with each other in the same culture media or matrix, indirect interaction involves different environments, allowing signaling and soluble factors to participate.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell differentiation in tissue models during interaction between cells can be studied using the Co-Cultured System to simulate cancer tumors, to assess the effect of drugs on therapeutic trials, and to study the effect of drugs on therapeutic trials.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The co-culture system in 3D models can predict the response to chemotherapy and endocrine therapy if the microenvironment defines biological tissue for the cells.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] A co-culture method is used in tissue engineering to generate tissue formation with multiple cells interacting directly.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Microfluidics technique is developed systems that can perform a process in a flow which are usually in a scale of micron.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Microfluidics chip are also known as Lab-on-a-chip and they are able to have continuous procedure and reaction steps with spare amount of reactants and space.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Such systems enable the identification and isolation of individual cells and molecules when combined with appropriate biological assays and high-sensitivity detection techniques.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] OoC systems mimic and control the microenvironment of the cells by growing tissues in microfluidics.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Combining tissue engineering, biomaterials fabrication, and cell biology, it offers the possibility of establishing a biomimetic model for studying human diseases in the laboratory.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] In recent years, 3D cell culture science has made significant progress, leading to the development of OoC.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] OoC is considered as a preclinical step that benefits pharmaceutical studies, drug development and disease modeling.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] OoC is an important technology that can bridge the gap between animal testing and clinical studies and also by the advances that the science has achieved could be a replace for in vivo studies for drug delivery and pathophysiological studies.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Besides the culture of well-established immortalised cell lines, cells from primary explants of a plethora of organisms can be cultured for a limited period of time before senescence occurs (see Hayflick's limit).
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cultured primary cells have been extensively used in research, as is the case of fish keratocytes in cell migration studies.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Plant cell cultures are typically grown as cell suspension cultures in a liquid medium or as callus cultures on a solid medium.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The culturing of undifferentiated plant cells and calli requires the proper balance of the plant growth hormones auxin and cytokinin.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cells derived from *Drosophila melanogaster* (most prominently, Schneider 2 cells) can be used for experiments which may be hard to do on live flies or larvae, such as biochemical studies or studies using siRNA.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Cell lines derived from the army worm *Spodoptera frugiperda*, including Sf9 and Sf21, and from the cabbage looper *Trichoplusia ni*, High Five cells, are commonly used for expression of recombinant proteins using baculovirus.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] For bacteria and yeasts, small quantities of cells are usually grown on a solid support that contains nutrients embedded in it, usually a gel such as agar, while large-scale cultures are grown with the cells suspended in a nutrient broth.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] The culture of viruses requires the culture of cells of mammalian, plant, fungal or bacterial origin as hosts for the growth and replication of the virus.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Whole wild type viruses, recombinant viruses or viral products may be generated in cell types other than their natural hosts under the right conditions.
[src:cell-culture/cell-culture] Depending on the species of the virus, infection and viral replication may result in host cell lysis and formation of a viral plaque.
